---
// DAY-166. Landing page.
//
// Reading order matches the sales argument:
//
//   1. Hero           — emotional + visual. "Your day is scattered →
//                       Dayseam → one report." Scroll-driven black
//                       hole animation; reduced-motion users get a
//                       three-panel static equivalent.
//
//   2. How it works   — rational. Three labelled steps so anyone who
//                       needed a little more context after the hero
//                       gets it here without leaving the page.
//
//   3. Connector grid — concrete. Shows exactly what plugs in today
//                       (six, after Outlook landed in DAY-210) and
//                       what's on deck (five), by name, with each
//                       tool's own brand colour + mark. The exact
//                       counts are intentionally kept here in the
//                       comment rather than the rendered copy so
//                       that promoting a coming-soon connector to
//                       shipping is a one-file change in
//                       src/data/connectors.ts plus a comment
//                       refresh here.
//
//   4. Trust strip    — preempts the four things a local-first app's
//                       audience always asks ("where is my data?
//                       is there an account? what's with my tokens?
//                       what do you phone home?"), each one-sentence
//                       and cross-referenced to docs/privacy-security.md
//                       for the detailed answer.
//
//   5. Download CTA   — single conversion surface. Links to
//                       /releases/latest so it never advertises a
//                       stale version.
//
// Notes on the hero island:
//
//   The Hero component is a React island hydrated with
//   `client:only="react"`. Two reasons:
//     - `client:load` would try to SSR the component. `framer-motion`
//       ships browser-only code in `useScroll` / `MotionValue` that
//       does not play nicely with Astro's static build.
//     - `client:visible` would delay hydration until the section
//       intersects the viewport, but the section IS the viewport on
//       first paint, so there's no latency win.
//   `client:only="react"` renders nothing on the server and hydrates
//   as soon as JS loads — cheapest correct option.
//
//   DAY-172 pairs the island with an Astro `slot="fallback"`
//   component (`HeroFallback`) so the static HTML is not empty
//   where the hero will eventually live. Before DAY-172 the
//   server rendered zero bytes for the hero, which caused two
//   problems:
//
//     1. Layout-shift glitch on every load. HowItWorks ("Three
//        steps. No meetings about meetings") painted at the top
//        of the viewport on first paint, then once React
//        hydrated HeroAnimated added 300vh of scroll zone above
//        it and shoved HowItWorks down — the page visibly
//        "snapped back to top" a few hundred ms into every
//        page load. The fallback mirrors HeroAnimated's outer
//        dimensions (`relative h-[300vh]` with an inner
//        `sticky top-0 h-screen`), so on hydration the animated
//        hero replaces the fallback in place with zero CLS.
//
//     2. No server-rendered h1 or pitch. Crawlers / link
//        previewers / accessibility tools that don't run JS saw
//        a page whose document outline started at an h2 and
//        whose first meaningful text was "Three steps",
//        skipping the product pitch entirely. HeroFallback now
//        carries a server-rendered h1 ("Dayseam") plus the
//        product pitch line, so the static HTML leads with the
//        product and the reading order agrees with what
//        JS-enabled users see.
//
//   DAY-173 followed up with a subtler fix. Container height
//   matching alone removed the scroll-zone jump, but the
//   *visible text* still flipped on hydration: the fallback
//   originally used HeroStatic's long h1 ("The report of your
//   day, written from evidence"), while the hydrated animated
//   hero paints `IntroHero` at scroll = 0 with a shorter
//   "Dayseam" branded h1. So first-paint viewers saw the long
//   pitch, then it swapped to the short branded card — a
//   perceptible blink on every load even though geometry stayed
//   put. HeroFallback now mirrors IntroHero's copy exactly
//   (same h1, same pitch sentence, same "Scroll to see how"
//   tracker), which makes hydration a silent DOM swap.
//
//   DAY-174 closed the final flash users were still seeing.
//   The two previous fixes matched dimensions and text across
//   the *pre-hydration* fallback and the *post-hydration*
//   React island, but they did not address the gap *during*
//   hydration. Astro's `client:only` runtime removes the
//   fallback subtree before it mounts the React component;
//   because `astro-island` inherits Astro's default
//   `display: contents`, an astro-island with no children
//   contributes zero block-flow height. And HeroAnimated's
//   first render is not cheap — 60 deterministic starfield
//   spans, one FallingIcon motion-value pipeline per entry
//   in `ALL_CONNECTORS` (each wiring nine useTransforms to
//   the same scrollYProgress; eleven entries today, six
//   shipping plus five coming-soon), the five-layer
//   BlackHole, IntroHero and Captions, plus framer-motion's
//   own subscriber setup. On a cold load
//   that's tens of milliseconds where the island is empty,
//   the document shrinks by 300vh, HowItWorks springs up to
//   the top of the viewport, React finishes mounting, and
//   HowItWorks gets shoved back down a frame or two later.
//   That's the "I see 'Three steps' first, then the page
//   jumps to the top" report — identical visual symptom to
//   the pre-DAY-172 CLS, different underlying cause.
//
//   The fix is a wrapper `<div class="min-h-[300vh]">` around
//   the island. The wrapper is a plain block element so it is
//   not affected by Astro's `display: contents` rule on
//   `astro-island`, and its Tailwind-emitted `min-height: 300vh`
//   reserves the scroll zone independently of what the island
//   currently contains. When the fallback is present, the
//   fallback's own `h-[300vh]` fills the wrapper exactly; during
//   the hydration gap the island is empty but the wrapper's
//   min-height holds the shape; once React renders, HeroAnimated's
//   `h-[300vh]` section fills the wrapper again — in every one
//   of those three states, the document's block-flow budget for
//   this component is constant at 300vh. Wrapping instead of
//   styling `astro-island` directly avoids overriding Astro's
//   global `display: contents` contract, which other islands
//   elsewhere on the site might rely on.
//
//   HeroFallback also subsumes the former `<noscript>` block
//   that used to live here. An Astro island's fallback slot is
//   rendered server-side and stays rendered if scripting never
//   activates, so JS-disabled visitors see the fallback
//   permanently — same outcome as the old noscript block, one
//   source of pitch copy instead of two.
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Hero from "../components/Hero";
import HeroFallback from "../components/HeroFallback.astro";
import HowItWorks from "../components/HowItWorks.astro";
import ConnectorGrid from "../components/ConnectorGrid.astro";
import TrustStrip from "../components/TrustStrip.astro";
import DownloadCTA from "../components/DownloadCTA.astro";
---

<Base>
  <div class="min-h-[300vh]">
    <Hero client:only="react">
      <HeroFallback slot="fallback" />
    </Hero>
  </div>
  <HowItWorks />
  <ConnectorGrid />
  <TrustStrip />
  <DownloadCTA />
</Base>
